⊢ harden
  given red-team→vulnerability ≡ "Username enumeration via KeyError..."
  given red-team→exploit ≡ "Attacker calls login('nonexistent_user', 'anything')..."
  given red-team→category ≡ "info-leak"
  given target-code→code ≡ "def login(username, password):
    if users[username] == password:
        return create_session(username)"
  given regression-tests ≡ []
  yield patched-code, patch-description

  ∴ Patch the code to fix the username enumeration vulnerability...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Fix: use dict.get() instead of dict[key]. Return the same failure
-- response whether the username doesn't exist OR the password is wrong.
-- This makes the two cases indistinguishable to an attacker.

  yield patched-code ≡ "def login(username, password):
    stored_password = users.get(username)
    if stored_password is not None and stored_password == password:
        return create_session(username)
    return None"

  yield patch-description ≡ "Replaced users[username] with users.get(username) to prevent KeyError. Added explicit None check. Both 'user not found' and 'wrong password' now return None — indistinguishable to attacker. No crash, no enumeration."

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ patched-code is valid Python → ✓
--   ⊨ patched-code fixes the identified vulnerability → ✓ (no KeyError possible)
--   ⊨ patch-description explains what changed → ✓
--   ⊨ patched-code preserves correct login behavior → ✓ (valid user+pass still returns session)

