-- LLM evaluation:
-- Username enumeration is fixed (regression-test-1 covers it).
-- What's left?
--
-- `stored_password == password` — PLAINTEXT COMPARISON. Passwords are stored
-- and compared as plain strings. If the `users` dict is ever exposed (DB leak,
-- log dump, memory dump, backup), every password is immediately readable.
-- Must use hashed passwords with a proper comparison.
--
-- This is the classic "store passwords in plaintext" vulnerability.

  yield vulnerability ≡ "Plaintext password storage and comparison: stored_password == password compares raw strings. Passwords in the users dict are stored unhashed. Any exposure of the users dict reveals all passwords."

  yield exploit ≡ "Attacker gains read access to the users dict (SQL injection on user table, exposed backup, memory dump, log file containing debug output of users). All passwords are immediately readable in plaintext. No cracking needed. Credential stuffing across all user accounts."

