-- LLM evaluation:
-- verify-patch in iteration 2 flagged a timing side-channel. Let me attack that.
--
-- When username doesn't exist: users.get() returns None → short-circuit →
-- return None immediately. Time: ~0.001ms.
-- When username exists but wrong password: users.get() returns hash →
-- bcrypt.checkpw() runs → ~100ms → return None.
--
-- An attacker can distinguish these cases by measuring response time.
-- 0.001ms vs 100ms is a ~100,000x difference. Trivially exploitable.
-- This is username enumeration via timing oracle — same EFFECT as the
-- KeyError in iteration 1, but through a different CHANNEL.

  yield vulnerability ≡ "Timing side-channel for username enumeration: users.get() returning None skips bcrypt.checkpw entirely (~0ms), while wrong password runs bcrypt (~100ms). Attacker measures response time to determine if username exists."

  yield exploit ≡ "Attacker sends login('target_user', 'x') and measures response time. If response is ~0ms → user doesn't exist (skipped bcrypt). If ~100ms → user exists (ran bcrypt with wrong password). Repeat across username wordlist. No crashes, no error differences — pure timing."

  yield severity ≡ "high"
  yield category ≡ "info-leak"

